entry.title: Significantly throttle DumpWithoutCrashing
entry.content:
base::debug::DumpWithoutCrashing() is being used as a drop-in

replacement for NOTREACHED() where instances are still being hit. This

comes with the unpleasant footgun where NOTREACHED() reporting basically

goes from once per process to once every 5 minutes. This risks flooding

the crash server which risks merges and respins.



Anyone who needs to dump at a more frequent interval should own that

footgun themselves (specify dumping interval and justify it).

entry.title: Prediction for ac=unrecognized: Metrics
entry.content:
When kAutofillPredictionsForAutocompleteUnrecognized is enabled, types

are predicted for ac=unrecognized fields (but they are not filled).

Because we don't want to change the baseline of the key metrics,

ac=unrecognized fields need to be excluded from them.



Since key metrics are logged through the form event logger, this is done

by changing BAM::GetEventFormLogger(FieldTypeGroup) to

BAM::GetEventFormLogger(AutofillField). With this interface, the

function can decide to return an event form logger only for

ac != unrecognized fields.

Some other calls to the event loggers exist, but they are independent

of individual fields/their predictions - and thus not affected.



The second category of metrics that we want to retain are metrics

reliant on the form types (= containing at least one address field).

Otherwise, forms completely annotated with ac=unrecognized suddently

become address forms. For this reason, FormStructure::GetFormTypes()

is changed.



There exist other metrics among Autofill's countless metrics which rely

on the field types in some way. For most of them, changes in the metrics

will be accepted. A notable example is the FieldPredictionQuality

metric.

Autofill.Autocomplete.{NotOff,Off}.* metrics are discussed here:

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4547325/comments/eb49ed47_0428b29f

entry.title: Check force-installed policy in HasIsolatedStorage()
entry.content:
This CL makes HasIsolatedStorage() more robust by also checking the

force-install extension policy in case the extension could not be

found in the extension registry. The login screen extension is not

present in any of the extension registry's lists during extension

update (when the old SW is unregistered and the new SW is registered).

The old SW's context is fetched by using HasIsolatedStorage(), and an

incorrect SW context is returned because HasIsolatedStorage() returns

false, leading to a failed unregistration.



Avoid edge cases such as this (and b/279763783) in the future by also

checking the force-installed policy.

entry.title: [fix-swo-violations] Fix sort comparison function
entry.content:
DownloadComparator assumes that its arguments do not alias the same

object. This assumption is used to check that IDs are unique.

However, this assumption is not guaranteed to hold by std::sort, and

the CHECK fails if _LIBCPP_DEBUG_STRICT_WEAK_ORDERING_CHECK is defined.

This CL gets rid of the assumption and only checks for uniqueness if

left-hand and right-hand sides of the compare function are different

objects.

entry.title: Make FontBuilder::CreateFont() lazier.
entry.content:
FontBuilder has a bit mask of font properties that are set, and only

does a hash table lookup to find the right font if any of them are.

However, we can be even lazier; if the set properties all match what

was already in the ComputedStyleBuilder, we can do an early abort.



This could happen if, for instance, we had a rule like



* { -webkit-font-smoothing: antialias; }



Every element will get font-smoothing: antialias, but only the root

element actually needs to change fonts over it. Of course, it's better

to set such a rule on the root, but there are many similar patterns

that are not as easy to get around.

entry.title: Annotate Cross task dangling pointers detected on Linux builds
entry.content:
This adds the DanglingAcrossTasks keyword and annotates raw_ptrs that

are "dangling cross task", i.e. that are freed and released in

different tasks.

These are more likely to allow UAFs and therefore are prioritized

over other dangling raw_ptr (Those remaining with DanglingUntriaged).



Protocol used:

1. Apply automatic dangling pointer annotation: crrev.com/c/4474553

2. Disable "DanglingUntriaged":

``` base/allocator/partition_allocator/pointers/raw_ptr.h:

constexpr auto DanglingUntriaged = base::RawPtrTraits::kEmpty ```

3. Configure Dangling pointer detection for cross tasks detection and logging only.

4. Run all tests using https://docs.google.com/document/d/1AMMERcqy0eafFWopUCHYsIKIKEp3J8DFxqW9UIbzIHo/edit?pli=1&resourcekey=0-e12-tlqsWfAOkle97uWw3w

5. Concatenate and filter output:

``` cat output_* | sort -nr | uniq | sed -e 's/\(.\)Found/\1\nFound/g' | grep -a -e "../../" | sed 's_^.*\.\./\.\./__' | sort | uniq > test_output_all

6. Apply the annotation using https://docs.google.com/document/d/1SGMZAaoEb6J0-NQO5V07TShxGAL5bxVN08TylBOrSCw/edit?usp=sharing

entry.title: Revert "Add metrics to confirm traffic difference between CSBRR and hit report"
entry.content:
This reverts commit d320106256ac5e8f1512f0846c01f0ec0c8f4345.



Reason for revert: Causes msan failures (e.g. https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/ci/Linux%20ChromiumOS%20MSan%20Tests/36726/overview) because hit_report->is_subresource is uninitialized in [here](https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:components/safe_browsing/core/browser/ping_manager_unittest.cc;l=557?q=ping_manager_unittest.cc:557)



Original change's description:

> Add metrics to confirm traffic difference between CSBRR and hit report

>

> The metrics added last week (https://crrev.com/c/4611266) show some

> evidence on the traffic difference between ClientSafeBrowsingReport

> and hit report:

> * For mainframe warnings, around 20% of reports are not sent because

> there is already a report being collected.

> * For subresource warnings, 90% of reports are not sent because

> there is already a report being collected.

> Now we have a good explanation for subresource warnings, but there is

> still a gap for mainframe warnings. Add more metrics to investigate

> further.

>

> Histograms added:

> 1 interstitial.CloseReason

> This is helpful to understand the proportion of reports skipped because

> users close the entire tab.

>

> 2 SafeBrowsing.ClientSafeBrowsingReport.HasThreatDetailsForTab.SecurityInterstitial

> This is a breakdown of the original histogram because I realize the

> result is diluted by other types of reports (mainly ads sample).

>

> 3 SafeBrowsing.ClientSafeBrowsingReport.HasThreatDetailsInContainer.SecurityInterstitial

> This is to double check that as long as the collector is found, the

> threat detail job is not null. In theory, it should always be not null.

>

> 4 SafeBrowsing.HitReport.IsSubresource

> This is to track the total volume of hit reports from the client-side

> and the break down between mainframe and subresource reports.

>
